ce:section.ce:para:
The selectivity of any sensing system plays a vital role of a sensor. The PL signal response of probe was monitored with respect to different analytes and presented in Fig. 6
                        . The PL signal quenching of NOCDs by organic pollutants was a quick reaction process and there is no change in the peak intensity up to 30 min by keeping the concentration constant in the solution (Figs. 7–9


                        ). Furthermore, the concentration of the organic pollutants was varied and the corresponding PL response of the solution was measured. By changing the concentration of the organic pollutants there is a drastic decrement in the NOCDs PL signal intensity with blue shift in the peak.

While a change in pH of organic dyes from 3 to 9 was found to decrease in the slope and increases the limit of detection and limit of quantification values (Figs. 11 and 12


                            and Table 1
                           ), which reveals the optical detection efficiency in surrounding medium pH values. At pH 3, the LOD and LOQ values corresponding to the organic dyes MB, MO, Rh6G and BrPB, are found to be 27, 20, 25 and 27 nM (LOD) and 90, 67, 83, and 90 nM (LOQ) respectively.

Similar to the above results, change in concentration of NOCDs in organic dyes from 4 to 7 μg/0.4 mL was found to increase in the slop and decrease the limit of detection and limit of quantification values (Figs. 13 and 14

                            and Table 2
                           ), which reveals the concentration of NOCDs will effect on the optical detection efficiency of organic pollutants. At the NOCDs concentration of 7 μg/0.4 mL for MB (0–100 μM), MO (0–40 μM), Rh6G (0–20 μM) and BrPB (0–40 μM), corresponding LODs were 0.9 μM, 28 nM, 0.4 μM and 0.7 μM respectively along with 3.0 μM, 93 nM, 1.3 μM and 2.3 μM respectively as their LOQs.
